Here is an example text element - 

"bTGzk": {
 "properties": {
 "text": {
 "entries": {
 "0": "Welcome to my fun webpage!"
 },
 "type": "TextExpression"
 },
 "height": 150,
 "left": 200,
 "top": 200,
 "width": 400,
 "zindex": 3
 },
 "type": "Text",
 "id": "bTGzi",
 "default\_name": "Text A",
 "style": "Text\_body\_large\_"
 }

"bTGzk" is a unique id to represent the key of this element child. The properties contain visual properties. the id "bTGzi" is the reference id used when any other workflows reference this element.

Yes, let me first teach you how to also represent a button in Lollipop JSON. Here is an example - 
"bTGzr": {
 "properties": {
 "text": {
 "entries": {
 "0": "Show Text "
 },
 "type": "TextExpression"
 },
 "height": 50,
 "left": 400,
 "top": 400,
 "width": 100,
 "zindex": 4
 },
 "type": "Button",
 "id": "bTGzm",
 "default\_name": "Button B",
 "style": "Button\_primary\_button\_"
 }

Notice that here, the type is Button.

Here is an example of a workflow child - 

"bTGzh": {
 "properties": {
 "element\_id": "bTGzc"
 },
 "type": "ButtonClicked",
 "id": "bTGzf",
 "actions": {
 "0": {
 "properties": {
 "element\_id": "bTGzi"
 },
 "type": "HideElement",
 "id": "bTGzl"
 }
 }
 }

You can see that the dictionary key to access this workflow child is "bTGzh". In the properties of this element, you see the input element id that represents the initial trigger. Then, in the actions, you see the properties that represents the element involved in the action, the type of action, and the id of the action. Notice that when a workflow refers to other elements, it uses those elements' reference ids. This action is of type "HideElement". So, when the input element is clicked, then "HideElement" is called on the element inside the action properties.

There are many different possible elements and workflows. But for now, let's only use the elements that we have discussed to create a very preliminary web page. Putting elements and workflows together, overall the structure looks a bit like this - 

"elements" : {
}
"workflows" : {}

Great, let's use the examples we've discussed so far to create a very simple web page using Lollipop JSON.

Here's an example with a text element, a button element, and a workflow that triggers when the button is clicked and hides the text element:
```css
{
  "elements": {
    "bTGzk": {
      "properties": {
        "text": {
          "entries": {
            "0": "Welcome to my fun webpage!"
          },
          "type": "TextExpression"
        },
        "height": 150,
        "left": 200,
        "top": 200,
        "width": 400,
        "zindex": 3
      },
      "type": "Text",
      "id": "bTGzi",
      "default_name": "Text A",
      "style": "Text_body_large_"
    },
    "bTGzr": {
      "properties": {
        "text": {
          "entries": {
            "0": "Hide Text"
          },
          "type": "TextExpression"
        },
        "height": 50,
        "left": 400,
        "top": 400,
        "width": 100,
        "zindex": 4
      },
      "type": "Button",
      "id": "bTGzm",
      "default_name": "Button B",
      "style": "Button_primary_button_"
    }
  },
  "workflows": {
    "bTGzh": {
      "properties": {
        "element_id": "bTGzm"
      },
      "type": "ButtonClicked",
      "id": "bTGzf",
      "actions": {
        "0": {
          "properties": {
            "element_id": "bTGzi"
          },
          "type": "HideElement",
          "id": "bTGzl"
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
In this example, we have a text element with the id "bTGzi" and a button element with the id "bTGzm". The workflow with the id "bTGzf" triggers when the button element is clicked, and its action hides the text element.

